## Verification Evidence Reports

Use repo-owned commands first. Optional HarnessForge helpers:

| Need | Command |
| --- | --- |
| Read-only verify plan | `harnessforge verify --target . --json` |
| Explicit runnable verify evidence | `harnessforge verify --target . --json --run` |
| Diff-aware check selection | `harnessforge plan --target . --since HEAD` |
| Unified review snapshot | `harnessforge report --target .` |

Store runnable evidence:

```bash
harnessforge verify --target . --run --json-report docs/harness/evidence/verify-<date>.json
harnessforge verify --target . --run --evidence-summary docs/harness/evidence/verify-summary-<date>.json
```

Use full JSON when diagnostics matter, or compact summary to omit stdout/stderr
previews. Review every `failed`, `timed_out`, or `blocked` check before claiming
success. Keep raw logs out of durable docs. Use agent-oriented failure messages:
what failed, why it matters, and where to repair. Verify output proves checks
were planned or run; it does not prove real-agent effectiveness and is optional
unless the repo owner adopts HarnessForge or its Action as a gate.

## When Checks Cannot Run

Record the command, exact reason, risk, next best check that ran, and whether
remote CI was intentionally skipped to control cost.
